# Onshape Sketches

A **sketch** is a 2D, constraint-solved profile on a plane (or planar face) inside
a Part Studio. It holds entities — lines, arcs, circles, points — pinned by
**constraints** (coincident, parallel, tangent…) and driven by **dimensions**
(lengths, radii, angles). Downstream features (extrude, revolve, sweep) consume a
sketch's closed **regions** to produce 3D geometry. A sketch lives in the feature
tree as a `BTMSketch` feature; this file covers **reading** its geometry — the
`/sketches` group under @onshape/partstudios.

## Model

- Addressed by `did/{wvm}/{wvmid}/eid` like the rest of the Part Studio group
  (see @onshape/partstudios): `{wvm}` is `w`/`v`/`m` (workspace / version /
  microversion). These are all **reads** — any coordinate is fine; there is no
  write endpoint here (you mutate a sketch through the feature envelope, below).
- A sketch is identified by its `sketchId` (= the owning sketch feature's
  `featureId`). `GET …/sketches` returns every sketch; the `sketchId` query filters
  to one; `…/sketches/{sid}/…` paths address one by id.
- What a sketch holds:
  - **plane** — the base plane or planar face the sketch is drawn on (origin +
    X/Y axes establishing its 2D coordinate frame).
  - **entities** — the geometry: line segments, arcs, circles, ellipses, splines,
    and points. Each carries its parameters in the sketch's 2D frame; with
    `output3D=true` the endpoint also gives their world (3D) coordinates.
  - **constraints** — the relations that remove degrees of freedom (coincident,
    horizontal, parallel, tangent, equal, symmetric…).
  - **dimensions** — the *measured* drivers (distance, radius, diameter, angle).
    A dimension is **not** stored in the read geometry as an editable number you
    POST here; it is a parameter on the sketch **feature** (see below).
- **sketch → consuming feature.** A sketch produces closed regions; an extrude /
  revolve / sweep references those regions through a `BTMParameterQueryList-148`
  (its `queries` point at the sketch's regions/edges). Edit the sketch and the
  consuming feature regenerates against the new regions. That binding lives on the
  consuming feature — see @onshape/features (Queries).

## A sketch IS a feature

Reading sketch geometry is a `/sketches` GET (this file). **Creating or editing**
a sketch — adding a line, moving a point, changing a dimension's value — is **not**
done here. A sketch is a `BTMSketch` feature in the Feature List, so it is written
through the same feature-update envelope as any feature: GET the feature, mutate
it, POST it back wrapped in `BTFeatureDefinitionCall-1406`. In particular a
**sketch dimension is a `BTMParameterQuantity` inside the sketch feature** (its
`expression`, e.g. `"25 mm"` or `"#width"`), exactly like an extrude depth. Defer
that whole flow to @onshape/features — don't reach for `/sketches` to change
geometry.

## Endpoints

| METHOD path | purpose |
|---|---|
| `GET …/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/sketches` | info for **all** sketches in the Part Studio: entities, constraints, dimensions. Query: `sketchId` (one sketch), `includeGeometry`, `output3D`, `curvePoints`, `configuration`, `linkDocumentId`. |
| `GET …/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/sketches/{sid}/tessellatedentities` | tessellation of one sketch — entities flattened to point polylines. Query: `entityId`, `angleTolerance`, `chordTolerance`, `configuration`. |
| `GET …/{wvm}/{wvmid}/e/{eid}/sketches/{sid}/boundingboxes` | one sketch's bounding box (`low*`/`high*`). |

Key query params on `GET …/sketches`:
- `includeGeometry` — include the entity geometry (entities/constraints/dimensions),
  not just the sketch list. Set it to get the actual geometry.
- `output3D` — also emit entity coordinates in the model's 3D frame, not only the
  sketch's local 2D frame.
- `curvePoints` — include sampled points along curved entities.
- `sketchId` — restrict the response to a single sketch.

## Shapes

`GET …/sketches` — the OpenAPI slice types the response as an open object (`{}`),
so the concrete keys are documented per spec / from observed responses rather than
a typed schema. With `includeGeometry=true` it returns a `sketches[]`, each sketch
carrying its `sketchId`, `featureId`, owning `plane`, and arrays of `geomEntities`
(lines/arcs/circles/points), `constraints`, and `dimensions`:

```json
{
  "sketches": [
    {
      "sketchId": "FID_sketch1",
      "featureId": "FID_sketch1",
      "plane": { "origin": [0,0,0], "normal": [0,0,1], "x": [1,0,0] },
      "geomEntities": [
        { "entityType": "lineSegment", "id": "line.1",
          "startPoint": [0,0], "endPoint": [0.05,0] },
        { "entityType": "circle", "id": "circle.1",
          "center": [0.025,0.025], "radius": 0.01 }
      ],
      "constraints": [
        { "constraintType": "HORIZONTAL", "entities": ["line.1"] }
      ],
      "dimensions": [
        { "dimensionType": "DISTANCE", "value": 0.05, "entities": ["line.1"] }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

> Field names above are per spec/observed (the slice gives `{}`); treat the exact
> keys as illustrative and read them off a live response. The runtime value that
> matters — *is there a sketch with entities* — is what the recipe asserts.

`GET …/sketches/{sid}/tessellatedentities` is likewise an open object (`{}` per
spec): each entity flattened to a polyline of points at the requested
chord/angle tolerance — the read-only render of the sketch curves.
`GET …/sketches/{sid}/boundingboxes` is the flat box shape shared with the Part
Studio: `{ "lowX":…, "lowY":…, "lowZ":…, "highX":…, "highY":…, "highZ":… }`.

## Recipe

Read-only against the **kb2** doc. Auth is HTTP Basic (`access:secret` over HTTPS,
per @onshape/auth — production should HMAC-sign). GET the sketches with geometry,
then verify a sketch exists and has entities.

```bash
export ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY=…  ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY=…
DID=378e93b0ad360aa043a0220b
WID=09273312fedee7bf3c3482ad
EID=a77918b06d5131918477a269
BASE=https://cad.onshape.com/api/v10

# GET all sketches, including their entity geometry
curl -sS -u "$ONSHAPE_ACCESS_KEY:$ONSHAPE_SECRET_KEY" \
  -H 'Accept: application/json' \
  "$BASE/partstudios/d/$DID/w/$WID/e/$EID/sketches?includeGeometry=true" \
  > sketches.json

# verify: at least one sketch, and the first sketch carries entities
jq -e '.sketches | length > 0' sketches.json >/dev/null \
  && jq -e '.sketches[0].geomEntities | length > 0' sketches.json >/dev/null \
  && echo "OK: $(jq -r '.sketches | length') sketch(es); first has \
$(jq -r '.sketches[0].geomEntities | length') entities" \
  || { echo "FAIL: no sketch with entities"; exit 1; }
```

Substitute `/w/$WID` → `/v/{vid}` or `/m/{mid}` to read a version/microversion.
To tessellate one sketch, take a `sketchId` from the response above and GET
`…/sketches/$SID/tessellatedentities`.

To **change** sketch geometry or a dimension's value (not just read it), build the
feature-update envelope and POST it to `…/features/featureid/{fid}` — that flow is
in @onshape/features (a sketch dimension is a `BTMParameterQuantity` on the
`BTMSketch` feature); the high-level edit+verify tool is @onshape/api.

See also: @onshape/partstudios (the owning element + the full `/partstudios`
group), @onshape/features (the BTMSketch feature-update envelope & queries),
@onshape/variables (`#name` expressions a sketch dimension can reference),
@onshape/auth (HMAC signing), @onshape/playwright (UI fallback for sketch edits
the API can't express).
